# <%= @project_name %>

Scaffolded <%= Atom.to_string(@runtime_class) %> connector package generated from the
workspace root.

## Runtime And Auth Posture

- runtime families: `<%= @runtime_families_literal %>`
- public auth binding is `connection_id`
- scaffolded default auth profile: `<%= @auth_profile_id %>`
- scaffolded management modes: `[:external_secret, :manual]`
- auth truth is authored in `supported_profiles`, `install`, and `reauth`; do
  not rely on provider-local hidden rules or repo-local conventions
- scaffolded install posture is explicit and non-hosted: `install.required: false`,
  `reauth.supported: false`
- deterministic execution still uses short-lived credential leases published by
  the connector contract
<%= if @include_runtime_metadata do %>- authored non-direct routing is published through `runtime.driver: "<%= @runtime_driver_id %>"` on the manifest instead of an implicit runtime default
<% else %>- this direct scaffold keeps runtime routing inside the package handler and does not publish Harness driver metadata
<% end %>

## Scaffold Output

This package starts with:

- one authored manifest contract built from `AuthSpec`, `CatalogSpec`, `OperationSpec`, and `TriggerSpec`
- one explicit authored auth profile plus connector-level union fields for
  scopes, management modes, durable secret fields, and lease fields
- one authored poll trigger skeleton with explicit checkpoint, dedupe, and ingress metadata
- one generated `Jido.Action` surface derived from the authored common operation
- one generated poll-backed `Jido.Sensor` surface derived from the authored common trigger
- one generated `Jido.Plugin` bundle derived from the shared consumer projection
- a runtime-class-appropriate handler skeleton
- a trigger handler skeleton for the generated poll surface
- a deterministic conformance companion module
- package-local tests that prove the scaffold passes the baseline conformance flow
<%= if @include_runtime_metadata do %>
- a package-local `runtime_drivers/0` proof hook plus deterministic Harness
  driver in `lib/` so downstream package tests can load the same conformance surface

This scaffold already publishes the selected Harness runtime driver
`<%= @runtime_driver_id %>` on the authored contract. It does not invent a
legacy bridge default. The generated non-direct common surface already carries
canonical `metadata.runtime_family` for the selected runtime family.
<% end %>

Generated actions, sensors, and plugins are derivative outputs only. Keep the
real source of truth in the authored manifest and use `consumer_surface.mode`
to decide whether a capability belongs on the curated common surface or stays
connector-local.

## What You Must Author

The scaffold is intentionally honest and minimal. It is the starting contract,
not the finished connector package. Replace these placeholders as you turn it
into a real connector:

Keep provider inventory, parity catalogs, and long-tail SDK helpers
connector-local unless you explicitly publish them through the manifest.
Target descriptors advertise compatibility and location only. They do not
override authored runtime.driver, runtime.provider, or runtime.options.

- auth, catalog, operation ids, trigger ids, schemas, scopes, and policy metadata in `[<%= @module_file %>]`
- `supported_profiles`, `default_profile`, `install`, `reauth`, and any
  connector-local `consumer_surface.mode` decisions in `[<%= @module_file %>]`
- if the connector wraps a provider SDK, add connector-local `install_binding.ex`
  and `client_factory.ex`
  `install_binding` should normalize install, reauth, manual-auth, or rotation
  secrets only.
  `client_factory` should build provider clients from credential leases only
  during runtime execution.
- handler logic in `[<%= @handler_file %>]`
- poll trigger logic in `[<%= @trigger_handler_file %>]`
- deterministic fixture expectations in `[<%= @conformance_file %>]`
<%= if @include_test_support do %>- deterministic Harness runtime behavior in `[<%= @conformance_harness_driver_file %>]`
<% end %>- this package `README.md` so it states the runtime families, supported auth
  profiles, install modes, published runtime slice, generated-vs-connector-local
  boundary, package-local verification commands, and live-proof status

## Proof Code Homes

Keep deterministic fixtures, companion modules, examples, scripts, and live
acceptance inside this package. Do not move connector proof code into the
workspace root.

Hosted webhook routing, async handlers, and app composition belong above the
connector package when that behavior is not part of the connector contract
itself.

Generated actions, sensors, and plugins remain derivative of the authored
manifest. They are not a second authoring plane.

## Package Verification

From the package root:

```bash
mix deps.get
mix compile --warnings-as-errors
mix test
mix docs
```

From the workspace root:

```bash
mix jido.conformance <%= @connector_module %>
mix ci
```

## Live Proof Status

No live proof is generated by default. Add package-local live acceptance only
when the real connector contract needs it, and keep that proof opt-in.

## Package Boundary

Do not widen this scaffold into root-level examples, provider code generation,
or app-only routing surfaces. Keep the connector package reviewable as an
isolated deliverable.

